  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering API Selection**\n\nI\'m presently evaluating the most suitable Gemini model. Initially, `gemini-3.5-flash` seemed promising for text applications. However, the documentation highlights an important instruction: avoid importing `@google/genai` or instantiating `GoogleGenAI` in client-side code unless the user specifically requests it. I am now considering what is safest to avoid accidental issues.\n\n\n**Clarifying API Endpoint Usage**\n\nI\'ve realized the prompt is very specific: \"Only Gemini API via fetch()\". This changes everything! The user intends direct API calls from client-side JavaScript. This directly implies fetching from the Gemini API endpoint, `https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models/gemini-1.5-flash:generateContent?key=${apiKey}` directly from the browser. No proxy is required! Now I am considering edge cases, such as handling a potential lack of API availability.\n\n\n**Implementing API Key Handling**\n\nI\'m now focused on implementing API key handling within the application. The user wants a key input bar at the top, which I believe is perfect. The key can be saved, then the input bar disappears, replaced by a \"MatchMood AI Ready\" badge. I\'m exploring auto-detection of `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY` or `process.env.API_KEY` in `vite.config.ts` to pre-populate or use the key if available. This is how the key fetch will proceed.\n\n\n**Refining API Key Strategy**\n\nI\'m now refining the API key strategy, having realized the implications of Vite\'s build process. The `vite.config.ts`\'s `define` configuration suggests a way to pre-configure the key, which would be ideal. I\'m exploring accessing `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY` or `process.env.API_KEY` during build time for automatic pre-filling of the API key, in case these are defined, or else fallback to asking the user to manually provide a key via the input bar. It seems possible to configure this in `index.html` as well.\n\n\n**Validating API Key Strategy**\n\nI\'ve got a fantastic new plan for API key management. Leveraging Vite\'s build-time replacement, I can access `process.env.API_KEY` or `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY` directly within the JavaScript code. If a key is defined at build time, it will be immediately available. If not, the user will be prompted to enter a key, which I can store in local storage after that. I\'m focusing on ensuring this pre-filling via `vite.config.ts` works perfectly.\n\n\n**Designing the Splash Screen**\n\nI\'m now diving into the splash screen design. The goal is a captivating, pure CSS animation. I\'m visualizing a full-screen, dark background with a bouncing cricket ball emoji, fading in text, and a shimmer effect. The bounce-in animation for the ball looks great. The objective is to make it incredibly smooth, using CSS keyframes. I am targeting a splash screen fade-out after 2.5 seconds.\n\n\n**Constructing Interface Components**\n\nI\'m now integrating the splash screen\'s key animations with the application\'s overall UI. I\'m focusing on a fixed header with a dark background and a key input bar at the top, which disappears upon saving. A \"MatchMood AI Ready\" badge will then appear. I\'m also planning a bottom navigation bar with \"Help\" and \"Fan\" tabs. The active tab will be distinguished by a gold indicator or underline.\n\n\n**Defining UI Navigation**\n\nI\'m now focused on tab navigation, aiming for a smooth 250ms fade and slide transition, using `opacity` and `transform`. The header title will be \"MatchMood AI\" in gold. The subtitle will be dynamic. For the Help tab, I\'ll use \"\360\237\217\237 Stadium Navigator \342\200\242 Wankhede\". I\'m planning an inline SVG of Wankhede Stadium with a green pitch, stands, and labeled gate markers that pulse when mentioned in the AI response.\n\n\n**Implementing Chat Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing the chat interface below the shortcut buttons. I am making user bubbles right-aligned with a MI Navy blue background and white text. AI bubbles will be left-aligned on white cards with dark text, with a small \"\342\234\250 MatchMood AI \342\200\242 Gemini 1.5 Flash\" footer. I\'m excited that I\'ll be able to toggle a pulse class on the SVG stadium elements based on the response.\n\n\n**Defining Chat Response Display**\n\nI\'m now designing the user and AI message display. I will add a \"\342\234\250\" label above the AI reply and include a typing indicator with three MI blue bouncing dots during AI generation. I\'ll make sure the chat smoothly scrolls to the newest message. The system prompt is now drafted: \"You are MatchMood AI, a stadium navigator.\"\n\n\n**Refining Button Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing the functionality for the shortcut buttons. I will be incorporating distinct visual cues: red for wickets (`#D32F2F`), blue for sixes (`#1565C0`), and gold for the MI chant (`#F9A825`). Each button will trigger a specific AI response, displayed in tinted cards with appropriate labels, and the chant will have a copy-to-clipboard button. I am considering a prediction section with an input field and predict button.\n\n\n**Finalizing Button Animations**\n\nI\'m now implementing the dynamic styling and the animations for button reactions, especially wickets, sixes, and chants. I\'ve got the scale on button press at 0.96 working perfectly. The AI responses are flowing and I am now ready to get the animated actions correct! It\'s shaping up to be a hit! \360\237\222\231 MatchMood AI\n\n\n**Adapting to Single-File Requirements**\n\nI\'m now shifting gears to accommodate a single-file application structure. The user wants the entire application within `index.html`. My plan is to replace `/index.tsx` and `App.tsx` with basic placeholders. I\'ll focus on ensuring that Vite correctly processes `index.html` as the entry point and avoid any unexpected conflicts. I will continue in this direction.\n\n\n**Confirming Single-File Structure**\n\nI\'m now fully committed to the single-file structure within `index.html`. My recent tests confirmed Vite\'s compatibility with inline JavaScript. The goal is now to migrate all existing JavaScript and CSS directly into the HTML file, completely removing any dependencies on `/index.tsx` or `/App.tsx`. I\'ll optimize for a clean, efficient structure.\n\n\n**Confirming File Structure**\n\nI am now focusing on setting up the remaining file structure. I\'ll make the `index.tsx` file empty. I\'ll make the `App.tsx` file empty. The goal is to make sure Vite compiles *only* the `index.html` file. I am working towards a single HTML file application. I will make sure Vite does not have any errors when it\'s being compiled.\n\n\n**Integrating Tailwind CSS**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating Tailwind CSS directly into the `index.html` file. My plan is to include the necessary scripts. Given the dependency `@tailwindcss/browser: ^4.1.10`, I can import it using importmap or use the CDN. I am examining how best to get Tailwind compilation support inside this context.\n\n\n**Implementing Tailwind Play**\n\nI\'m now fully committed to using the Tailwind Play CDN to meet the single-file requirements. It ensures reliable, out-of-the-box support without server compilation, satisfying the \"ONE HTML file\" constraint. I\'ve realized its compatibility with custom styles makes it ideal.\n\n\n**Defining Custom Theme Colors**\n\nI\'m now implementing custom theme colors. Considering the previous Tailwind Play approach, the plan is to define the color scheme directly within the `tailwind.config` JavaScript object. I\'ve decided to define colors like MI Navy, MI Gold, and Wicket Red. The goal is to ensure a unified and visually appealing aesthetic, using robust, compatible configuration methods.\n\n\n**Defining Animation Structure**\n\nI am now focusing on implementing the animations and am making progress with defining the structure. I\'m exploring the CSS framework. I\'ll utilize keyframes for the splash screen animations and integrate them with the overall app\'s responsive design. I\'m ready to fine-tune the confetti animations.\n\n\n**Defining Animation Details**\n\nI am now structuring the confetti and fireworks animations in detail. The \"WICKET!\" confetti involves spawning 80 particles upward with varied trajectories and colors. Conversely, the \"SIX!\" fireworks will emanate radial lines from the tap point, fading outwards. For the \"Typing...\" indicator, I have implemented three bouncing dots.\n\n\n\n**Refining Visual Effects**\n\nI\'m now refining the visual effects. I\'m focusing on tab switching with a slide and fade-in, and implementing a pulsing glow for stadium gates, which looks incredible. I am planning a CSS active scale button effect to create a great button press effect. I\'m working to make the splash screen fade out smoothly and also fade in new content, to create a great flow.\n\n\n**Defining API Request Structure**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the direct Gemini API call details. I\'ve confirmed the POST endpoint is `https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models/gemini-1.5-flash:generateContent?key=${apiKey}`. I\'m structuring the request body with \"contents\" and \"generationConfig\". I am also considering the distinct system prompts for \"Help Mode\" and \"Fan Mode\" with specific instructions.\n\n\n**Structuring API Interactions**\n\nI\'m now integrating system instructions directly into Gemini API requests. I am planning a structure incorporating specific instructions for six reactions, chants, and predictions, complete with MI signature and a win percentage. I am also working on configuring for timeouts, including the \"retry\" suggestion, and will use the model gemini-1.5-flash.\n\n\n**Implementing Request Abort Logic**\n\nI\'m now implementing request abort logic using `AbortController` in the JavaScript fetch function. If the Gemini API request exceeds an 8-second timeout, the fetch is aborted and the user is shown a \"tap to retry\" prompt, which is excellent. I\'ll test it thoroughly.\n\n\\n\\n\n\nI\'m now elaborating on the stadium SVG map\'s interactive logic. The map will have a green pitch and four labeled gate markers. When the AI mentions a specific gate (e.g., \"Gate 1\"), the corresponding marker will pulse and glow green, providing a great visual indication. I\'ve drafted a parser script for this purpose.\n\n\n**Enhancing Button Interactions**\n\nI\'m now integrating shortcut button functionality within the UI\'s existing flow. When a button is tapped, the corresponding message will instantly appear as a user bubble in the chat, immediately triggering a typing indicator and API call. Subsequently, the AI\'s response will display with a smooth scroll, and the parser will highlight gates mentioned in its response.\n\n\n**Verifying Gate Pulse Logic**\n\nI\'ve clarified the interaction logic for stadium gate markers. Gate pulsing is triggered only by the AI\'s reply explicitly mentioning a gate, ensuring intuitive visual feedback and a seamless experience. The \"My Gate\" and \"Nearest Food\" buttons will have the AI mention a gate in its response, which triggers the pulse. I am now proceeding with the SVG design.\n\n\n**Defining Stadium Visualization**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the stadium SVG visualization. I am structuring the cricket pitch as a rectangle, and adjusting the outfield as a center-aligned ellipse with custom gate placements. The goal is a visually appealing and accurately represented stadium with clearly labeled gate positions, ready for dynamic highlighting.\n\n\n**Visualizing Stadium Components**\n\nI\'m now implementing the SVG gate markers using small colored circles with pulsing animations, and structuring their placement within the stadium visualization. I\'m excited by how well it fits the design. I\'m focusing on layout and positioning.\n\n\n**Refining Stadium Visualization**\n\nI\'m now refining stadium visualization details within the SVG, focusing on gate marker designs. I\'m adding a white border to them. I\'ve integrated a \"Gate 1 (West)\" label using text tags. I\'m excited at how the pulsing circle design is taking shape, and is ready for integration.\n\n\n**Finalizing Stadium Gate Design**\n\nI\'m now implementing the SVG gate markers using small, colored circles with pulsing animations, and structuring their placement within the stadium visualization. I\'m focusing on layout and positioning. I have added the gate glow effect and have integrated the text label for each marker.\n\n\n**Refining Gate Highlighting Logic**\n\nI\'m implementing dynamic gate highlighting within the SVG. The plan is to trigger a pulsing green glow on a gate when the AI\'s response mentions that gate. This will involve adding a `.pulse-active` class to the glowing circle and changing its color to green via CSS using keyframes. I am confident this visual cue will be intuitive.\n\n\n**Verifying Animation Integration**\n\nI am now verifying the integration of visual cues. I\'ve successfully linked the activation of the `.pulse-active` class and `.pulse-dot-active` to the AI\'s response, turning the gate marker pulsing green as requested, which looks fantastic. I am excited to check the animations on the buttons!\n\n\\n\\n\n\n**Implementing Confetti Logic**\n\nI\'m now incorporating confetti logic. The plan is to trigger 80 particles with random colors and physics, using vanilla JavaScript. I\'ve designed the color palette and the basic particle generation, with the use of a simple `shapeClass` property. I am going to build this using `className` to set the shapes and colors of these particles.\n\n\n**Fine-Tuning Particle Effects**\n\nI\'m presently optimizing the confetti particle properties. I\'m focusing on refining initial positions, angles, velocities, and gravity parameters to achieve visually appealing trajectories. I\'m aiming for balanced, realistic particle physics. The plan is to continue with this fine tuning.\n\n\n**Optimizing Confetti and Fireworks**\n\nI\'ve successfully implemented both confetti and fireworks animations without external libraries! Confetti now uses realistic physics. Fireworks generate radial lines from tap points. I\'m focusing on refining particle properties and the fireworks trigger function to provide an immersive experience, specifically the `triggerFireworks` function.\n\n\n**Refining Fireworks Effects**\n\nI\'m now optimizing the fireworks\' visual dynamics based on new insights. I\'m focusing on improved line expansion and outward translation for enhanced effect. The current plan includes precise timing and opacity adjustments, to optimize the burst. This new design is great!\n\n\n**Refining API Key Handling**\n\nI\'m now integrating API key validation and fallback mechanisms. The logic begins by checking local storage for a key. If none is found, I\'ll attempt to access `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY` or `process.env.API_KEY`, which Vite defines at build time. Only if none are present will a user input bar be shown. I am prioritizing robust API key management.\n\n\n**Enhancing API Key Integration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on directly connecting the API key management with the user interface. If a key is found, the input bar will instantly transform into the \"\342\234\205 MatchMood AI Ready\" pill, perfectly integrated into the header. I\'m prioritizing user experience with a clean transition between these states.\n\n\n**Managing User Interactions**\n\nI\'m now integrating the toast component for displaying key-related and API errors. A red toast appears with \"\360\237\224\221 Please add your Gemini API key to continue\" if no key is found. An API error message will say \"MatchMood AI is catching its breath, try again! \360\237\231\217\". A timeout triggers \"Taking longer than usual... tap to retry.\" I\'m structuring these messages, and implementing the visual components.\n\n\n**Structuring Chat Welcome**\n\nI\'m now integrating the initial chat message for the \"Help\" tab, providing a friendly welcome and suggesting shortcut interactions. I\'ll include the necessary shortcut prompts to ensure users get the smoothest experience possible. Now, I will format the help message.\n\n\n**Refining Gemini Request Handling**\n\nI\'m now refining the Gemini request flow based on shortcut button presses. I\'ve designed the process: clicking a shortcut appends the user\'s message to the chat and triggers a typing indicator. Then, `askGemini` obtains the API key, constructs the request, and implements an 8-second timeout using `AbortController` to handle potential API delays, as well as error handling. This is very good, and I am ready to implement this!\n\n\n**Refining Error Handling**\n\nI\'m now implementing a \"tap to retry\" action for API timeouts. By making the timeout error message clickable or including a link, the user can easily re-initiate the API request, ensuring a better user experience. This design directly addresses the prompt for handling timeouts.\n\n\n\n**Designing Response Cards**\n\nI\'m now designing the dedicated response cards, specifically for the fan interactions. There will be distinct card styles for wickets (red), sixes (blue), and chants (gold). I will include a \"\360\237\223\213 Copy Chant\" button for the gold chant card, which changes to \"\342\234\205 Chant Copied!\" on click for a short duration. The design aims for a sleek, dynamic display using a dedicated `#fan-response-container`.\n\n\n**Refining Response Container**\n\nI\'m now refining the dedicated response cards, and the predictions container inside Fan Mode. I\'ll add distinct card styles. This avoids clutter and refines the UI. I am considering system prompts for Help and Fan modes, defining the interaction style.\n\n\n**Refining Reaction Prompts**\n\nI\'m now refining the button prompts to perfectly match user expectations. The wicket prompt is now `\"A wicket just fell! Give me a wild wicket reaction.\"`, and the six prompt: `\"A massive six has been hit! Give me an explosive six reaction.\"`. The chant prompt remains unchanged. The label will always be `\"\342\234\250 MatchMood AI \342\200\242 Gemini 1.5 Flash\"`.\n\n\n**Defining App Structure**\n\nI am now focusing on the app\'s structural elements and color palette. I\'ll center the app using a responsive wrapper with a dark header, dynamic subtitle, and colored button highlights. I\'m prioritizing a mobile-first design with a clear visual hierarchy. I am also implementing the dedicated color scheme as described.\n\n\n**Confirming Single-File Compilation**\n\nI\'m verifying that Vite successfully compiles a single HTML file without referencing `/index.tsx` or `/App.tsx`. After removing the React script import and ensuring all content resides within `index.html`, I am confirming the build process works as expected with a static HTML file. The key is removing the references.\n\n\n**Simplifying Entry Point**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the implications of a single-file structure for our build process. I\'m exploring how Vite handles `index.html` as the entry point in the absence of traditional TypeScript files. The plan is to verify a working scenario, removing the React mount point. I will now integrate the HTML inside of the page.\n\n\n**Defining HTML Shell Structure**\n\nI\'m now structuring the basic HTML shell, envisioning a responsive design that looks like a device frame on desktop and occupies the full viewport on mobile. This will include a fixed header and footer navigation bar. My immediate goal is to establish a modern, clean visual framework. I will start with a full-screen, dark background with the cricket ball emoji.\n\n\n**Structuring Chat Welcome**\n\nI\'m now integrating the initial chat message for the \"Help\" tab to provide a friendly welcome with suggested shortcut interactions. I will be sure to include these suggested shortcuts. I am working on getting the formatting completed.\n\n\n**Structuring Fan Mode Interface**\n\nI\'m now integrating the fan mode user interface elements, including the live match banner, reaction buttons, and prediction panel.  I\'m focusing on the distinct card styles for each reaction (wicket, six, chant) to be visually distinctive, and have a copy-to-clipboard function for the chant cards. I\'m excited by this.\n\n\n**Implementing Error Handling**\n\nI\'m now implementing floating notifications for errors such as missing API keys, timeouts, or API downtime. I\'m focusing on these elements: full-screen canvas layers for high-resolution animations! I\'m now verifying the SVG stadium map, and working to perfect its design. I\'m designing a CSS keyframe for a pulsing, glowing gate animation, using the `@keyframes pulseGlow` logic.\n\n\n**Refining Gate Animation Logic**\n\nI\'m now implementing the gate highlighting via a pulsing outer circle within the SVG. This uses a separate `<circle>` element with a CSS animation (`pulseRing`) for the pulsing effect, which I will toggle via a class. The CSS animation provides a consistent and efficient animation. The animation\'s control looks excellent!\n\n\n**Confirming API Model Selection**\n\nI\'m now confirming the API model. While other Gemini models are available, the user\'s explicit request for \"Gemini 1.5 Flash\" dictates that the fetch URL must target `models/gemini-1.5-flash` endpoint. This is to ensure compliance.\n\n\n**Confirming API Model Request**\n\nI\'m now confirming that the API model, `gemini-1.5-flash`, is the appropriate choice, and will be incorporated into the API model fetch URL. I\'m also preparing to use this exact name as the application label, \"MatchMood AI \342\200\242 Gemini 1.5 Flash\", for consistency. I am verifying the payload structure that I will send with my request.\n\n\n**Verifying Build Configuration**\n\nI\'m now confirming the build configuration for the single-file structure. After emptying `/index.tsx` and `/App.tsx`, I\'ll verify the Vite build process and ensure there are no errors. The goal is a clean build, treating `index.html` as the sole entry point, without React or TypeScript compilation issues. This focuses on empty files, and a single, self-contained HTML file.\n\n\n**Revising Single-File Strategy**\n\nI\'m now reconsidering the single-file approach given the `tsconfig.json` implications. It looks like leaving `/App.tsx` and `/index.tsx` as they are now may result in unexpected build issues, or at least a redundant TypeScript compilation step. I could move the React setup into `index.tsx` instead of `App.tsx` and have the entire MatchMood AI inside `index.tsx`, since I have a React set up. However, the requirement is \"ONE HTML FILE\", so I must remove all other files! I will proceed by emptying all of them.\n\n\n**Confirming Single-File Compilation**\n\nI\'m verifying that Vite will compile a single `index.html` file after the removal of `index.tsx` and `App.tsx` and the incorporation of all code into `index.html`. This directly aligns with user requirements for an all-inclusive HTML structure, removing unnecessary build complexity.\n\n\n**Creating HTML Entry Point**\n\nI\'m now establishing `index.html` as the central entry point for the application, ensuring it contains all the necessary HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. I\'m focusing on a responsive and functional layout. The plan is to create `index.html` file and work from there.\n\n\n"
