  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering HTML Configuration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on `index.html`. My main question is about the consequences of Vite specifying `/index.tsx` within it. Specifically, what if that reference is removed? Can we achieve standard vanilla HTML and JS functionality in this scenario, or are we reliant on the original setup?\n\n\n**Confirming Tailwind Implementation**\n\nI\'ve confirmed Tailwind\'s browser engine is installed in the template. The optimal approach appears to be loading it directly via CDN in `index.html`. This bypasses any compile steps. We can use the `<script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@tailwindcss/browser@4\"></script>` tag, which is very reliable for single-file preview pages. I\'m now verifying the overall layout.\n\n\n**Defining HTML App Structure**\n\nI\'m now detailing the HTML app structure for the single-page mobile app. The styling starts with a deep dark slate background, `#1C1C2E`. The splash screen, for 2.5 seconds, will be full-screen, with the ID `splash-screen`. I\'ll use absolute/fixed positioning and center everything. A large bouncing cricket ball emoji, \360\237\217\217, with a CSS animation, is key, along with \"MatchMood AI\", tagline, and \"Powered by Gemini\" text.\n\n\n**Structuring Mobile App Design**\n\nI\'m now sketching the mobile app\'s core layout. I\'m focusing on the fixed header, particularly the API key bar at the top with input and save buttons. I\'ll need to use local storage and the environment to prepopulate the key field, and then display a \"ready\" badge after saving. Underneath, a title and dynamic subtitle are based on the selected tab (Help or Fan).\n\n\n**Designing Mobile App Layout**\n\nI\'m now detailing the help and fan modes. Specifically, the staggered tab transition is key: 250ms fade with slide animation. The navigation footer, with its white background and subtle border, is taking shape, and the active tab will feature the vibrant `#004C97` with a gold underline. I\'m focusing on mobile frame aesthetics. I\'m also planning the stadium navigator with an SVG Wankhede.\n\n\n**Implementing Chat Functionality**\n\nI\'m now implementing the chat functionality. I\'m focusing on parsing the AI\'s response for specific gate mentions to trigger marker pulses. I\'m also planning the shortcut buttons: rounded, full-width, bold, and active on select. I\'m also preparing to create the chat interface. It will feature user messages on the right and MatchMood AI on the left, with the respective stylings. I am also working on the typing indicator. Finally, auto-scrolling is also being implemented.\n\n\n**Designing Celebration Buttons**\n\nI\'m now detailing the celebration button designs. The \"WICKET!\" button will be red and trigger a confetti explosion. \"SIX!\" will be deep blue, leading to fireworks, and \"MI Chant\" will be gold, with an AI-generated chant. I am also working on the prediction block, with a text input, and gold predict button. The results will be displayed in an amber card.\n\n\n**Defining Branding & Error Handling**\n\nI\'m now integrating the branding: \"\342\234\250 MatchMood AI \342\200\242 Gemini 1.5 Flash\" above the AI bubbles and the footer \"MatchMood AI \342\200\224 Powered by Gemini 1.5 Flash | GDG Rajkot\". I\'m also planning the error handling: a red toast and API key field highlight for missing keys, a chat message for fetch failures (\"MatchMood AI is catching its breath, try again! \360\237\231\217\"), and a timeout message after 8 seconds (\"Taking longer than usual... tap to retry\"). I\'ll be focusing on a single, clean `index.html` page. Also, I\'m noting the mapping of `/index.tsx` to `/index.html`. I\'ll consider keeping or removing `/App.tsx`.\n\n\n**Refining HTML Consolidation**\n\nI\'m now revising the approach for a single HTML file. The prompt\'s emphasis on \"ONE HTML file. All CSS and JS inside\" is key. I\'m moving toward an HTML-centric design, which means eliminating external JavaScript and CSS references. The goal is to embed all functionality directly within `index.html`, which leads to a clean, self-contained solution.\n\n\n**Verifying HTML Server Behavior**\n\nI\'ve confirmed the development server correctly serves `index.html` regardless of `<script>` tags, and the browser executes standard JavaScript within `<script>` tags, even with Vite. I\'m now verifying the build process and how Vite handles raw JavaScript and CSS within `index.html`, specifically checking if they are correctly rolled up into the `dist/` directory. Also, I\'m checking the `tsconfig.json` to ensure TypeScript doesn\'t obstruct a build with unused files. Finally, I\'ve confirmed that the build script just runs `vite build`, meaning it skips TypeScript compilation by default.\n\n\n**Consolidating Mobile Layout**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a completely self-contained `index.html`. My approach is to ensure a pristine user experience by embedding all CSS and JavaScript directly. I am keeping `/index.tsx` as is, since it will be unused. I\'m focusing on a mobile-responsive design, now matching the detailed color scheme, fonts, spacing, shadows, and overall feel. I am also working on a visual preview simulation for desktop to show an iPhone-like frame.\n\n\n**Designing Visual Overlays**\n\nI\'m now detailing the visual effects. I\'m prioritizing the fireworks and confetti animations, specifically focusing on generating these using a `<canvas>` element for performance. The `effects-canvas` will span the full screen, and all animations will run at a consistent 60 FPS. I\'m planning to dynamically generate the CSS for the confetti and using JavaScript to create both confetti and firework effects on the canvas.\n\n\n**Implementing Visual Effects**\n\nI\'m now implementing the visual effects: confetti and fireworks. I\'ve focused on `startConfetti()` for \"WICKET!\", spawning 80 particles with random velocities, colors, gravity, and air resistance. The fireworks for \"SIX!\" now involve radially outward flying particles with sparkles. Both animations are rendered on a `<canvas>`, ensuring smooth performance. I\'m also planning the SVG Cricket Stadium representing Wankhede Stadium.\n\n\n**Mapping Stadium Interactions**\n\nI\'m now integrating the stadium SVG with dynamic gate highlighting. My focus is on writing the JavaScript logic to scan the AI response text for gate mentions. I\'m planning to use regex for case-insensitive matching. Upon detection, I will trigger a CSS animation to pulse the corresponding gate dot and make it glow brightly on the map. I\'m also ensuring the stadium SVG represents the key visual details (field, pitches, boundary, and gate dots with standard labels).\n\n\n**Defining System Instructions**\n\nI\'m now writing the system instructions for \"Help\" and \"Fan\" modes. For \"Help,\" I\'m focused on clarity and brevity, guiding users to Wankhede Stadium locations with helpful bonus tips. For \"Fan,\" I\'m crafting a high-energy persona with cricket slang and specific reaction styles for wickets, sixes, and chants. These prompts are designed for maximum impact within concise responses.\n\n\n**Configuring API Key Management**\n\nI\'m now detailing the API key bar at the top, which will include an input field and save button. Local storage will handle key persistence; on load, the bar auto-populates the input from `localStorage`, if available. I\'ll implement a \"ready\" badge (or a settings icon) to signal API key status and facilitate updates. The default model for API calls will be `gemini-1.5-flash`, as requested.\n\n\n**Refining Chat Interaction**\n\nI\'m now detailing the chat interface\'s auto-scrolling and user interactions. I\'ve designed shortcut buttons to send predefined prompts directly, such as \"My Gate,\" \"Nearest Food,\" \"Restroom,\" and \"First Aid,\" which simplifies user input. The user\'s chat bubbles will have a MI Navy blue background with white text, and the AI\'s response will appear in white cards with dark text, and a prefix \"\342\234\250 MatchMood.\" I\'m updating to the specific model endpoint: `gemini-1.5-flash`.\n\n\n**Implementing Chat and Event Handling**\n\nI\'m now implementing the chat behavior and event triggers for \"Fan Mode.\" The typing indicator will feature three MI blue bouncing dots during AI response fetching. We will also automatically scroll to the bottom of the chat whenever a new message is appended. I\'m building out the full-screen animations for the celebration events. Confetti on WICKET and fireworks for SIX. I\'m integrating the Gemini prompts for \"wild wicket reaction,\" \"explosive six reaction,\" and a \"four-line MI chant\".\n\n\n**Constructing a Single-File App**\n\nI\'m now writing all HTML5/CSS3/ES6 code directly into `index.html`. I\'m starting by verifying the structure and the standard HTML tags. I\'m focusing on incorporating the Tailwind CDN, beautiful fonts, custom animations, the API connection, and error handling for a polished app. I\'m checking the design details for colors and visual appeal. I\'m also planning the user\'s interaction \"Type anything or tap Predict.\"\n\n\n"
